craft_trajectory_plotter.py README


is a stand‑alone Python program that ties together the two files you already have  

baseline_foam_map.py – the static foam‑grid (no disturbances)  
solar_foam_animation.py – the time‑dependent foam‑distortion produced by the Sun, planets, moons …

and turns any spacecraft (or probe) ephemeris into a 3‑D animated trajectory that can be visualised together with the foam field in the same open‑source visualiser you used before (Paraview, Blender, three‑js, …).

1️⃣  What the program does



Feature
How it is realised
Master‑Equation reference



Loads the baseline foam grid
baseline_foam_map.FoamMap (same class you already built)
Part 1‑3 – the foam‑fluid properties (ρ_f, σ_f, η_f)


Loads the pre‑computed foam‑distortion frames
Reads the foam_XXXXX.vts files written by solar_foam_animation.py
Part 5 – foam‑field energy, Eq. 5.17 (used as phi_dist)


Ingests NASA‑mission / probe data
CSV or JSON files containing time‑stamped position, velocity, attitude.  The reader can also call SPICE (via spiceypy) if you supply a kernel.
Part 8 – Navigator mathematics (Eq. 8.5, 8.6) – the program treats the supplied ephemeris as the “true” trajectory; later you can replace it with a foam‑driven navigation solution.


Interpolates the craft state for any simulation time
Linear interpolation in time (or cubic spline – toggle with --interp spline).
Eq. 8.6 (proper‑time integral) gives the idea of a smooth trajectory.


Writes per‑frame data
Two files per frame: <br>1️⃣ foam_XXXXX.vts – unchanged, contains the foam scalar (phi_dist) and vector (foam_force). <br>2️⃣ craft_XXXXX.json – list of all active crafts with position (AU), velocity (AU day⁻¹), speed (km s⁻¹), and Euler angles (deg).
The JSON side‑car is the same format used by solar_foam_animation.py for the planets, so the visualiser can treat probes exactly like bodies.


Supports many crafts
The JSON contains an array; you can add as many rows as you like.
Part 8 – “multiple travel modes” → each craft is just another “travel mode”.


Rewind / fast‑forward
The frames are numbered sequentially; any VTK‑aware visualiser can scrub through them. You can change the playback speed simply by changing the time‑step (--dt‑hours).
The viewer’s timeline is the analogue of the “proper‑time integral” (Eq. 8.6).


Future‑proof
The program does not modify the foam field – it only reads it.  When you later generate a disturbed foam map (e.g. from real Voyager data) you can drop the new foam_XXXXX.vts files in the same folder and the craft visualisation will automatically show the craft moving through the new disturbances.
Part 9 – “Emergent gravity & cosmology” – you can later replace the static phi_dist with a measured one.



2️⃣  How to run it

          
            
            
          
     		# 1️⃣  Install the tiny extra dependency (for optional SPICE support)
	pip install numpy pandas tqdm spiceypy  # spiceypy is optional; you can omit it

	# 2️⃣  Use craft_trajectory_plotter.py
	# 3️⃣  Prepare a CSV (or JSON) with the probe data – see the “Data format” section below.

	# 4️⃣  Example command
		python craft_trajectory_plotter.py \
 				   --start "2025-01-01T00:00:00" \
   			      --end   "2025-12-31T00:00:00" \
  			      --dt-hours 2 \
 				   --probe-file ./probes/voyager1.csv \
 				   --output ./animation_frames
      
--dt-hours controls the playback resolution – a smaller value gives smoother motion (but more files).  
--interp can be linear (default) or spline for smoother interpolation.  
Add as many --probe-file arguments as you like – each file becomes a separate craft.

Open the folder ./animation_frames in Paraview (or Blender) and load the VTK files (foam_*.vts). Then load the matching JSON files (craft_*.json) as a Table To Points source; the colour and size can be driven by the speed_kms field or by a user‑defined tag.

3️⃣  Data format for a probe / spacecraft
A CSV file must have a header and the following columns (all values are in AU unless otherwise noted):



Column
Meaning
Units / format



time_iso
ISO‑8601 timestamp (e.g. 2025-01-01T12:00:00)
string


x
X‑coordinate in AU (heliocentric)
float


y
Y‑coordinate in AU
float


z
Z‑coordinate in AU
float


