5️⃣  HOW TO VIEW THE RESULT
In Paraview

Open the first VTK file (foam_00000.vts).  
Apply → colour by phi_dist (blue‑to‑red).  
Open the matching JSON (craft_00000.json) → Filters → Table To Points.  
Set X Column = pos_au[0], Y Column = pos_au[1], Z Column = pos_au[2].  
Choose Glyph → Sphere and map the Scale to speed_kms (or a constant).  
Map the Color to color_rgb (use a Calculator to convert 0‑255 → 0‑1).


Play the animation using the VCR controls – Paraview will load the next VTK/JSON pair automatically if the file pattern is set to foam_%05d.vts and craft_%05d.json.  
Rewind / fast‑forward – just scrub the timeline; the viewer will instantly show the craft at any frame, together with the foam‑distortion “waves” it crosses.

In Blender (with the Import‑VTK add‑on)

File → Import → VTK Structured Grid → pick foam_00000.vts.  
Use a Material that reads the attribute phi_dist and drives a ColorRamp (blue‑to‑red).  
Write a tiny Python script that, on each frame change, reads the JSON side‑car, creates a UV Sphere for each craft, sets its location (pos_au → multiply by AU_M), scales it by speed_kms, and colours it with color_rgb.  
Set the frame range to the number of generated files (0 … n_frames‑1).  The script can be attached to a frame change handler so that the scene updates automatically as you scrub.


6️⃣  EXTENDING THE PIPELINE



What you might add later
Where to modify



Real foam disturbances (e.g. Voyager‑1 measured foam)
Replace the static foam_XXXXX.vts files with a new set generated from the measured data; the same JSON side‑car will automatically show the craft moving through the new ripples.


Foam‑driven navigation (instead of a pre‑computed ephemeris)
In Craft.state_at() call a physics engine that solves the Navigator equations (§8) using the local foam_force field read from the VTK file.


Mission‑specific metadata (e.g. payload mass, thrust)
Extend the JSON side‑car with extra keys; the visualiser can display them as tool‑tips.


Higher‑resolution visualisation
Reduce GRID_SPACING_AU in baseline_foam_map.py and re‑run solar_foam_animation.py. The trajectory program will automatically pick up the finer VTK files.


Web‑based player
Export the VTK files to glTF (via vtk → pygltflib) and ship the JSON side‑car; a three‑js app can then animate the craft and colour‑code the foam.



TL;DR
Save the script as craft_trajectory_plotter.py.Run it with the start/end dates, time‑step, and one or more probe CSV/JSON files.It will produce a folder that contains  

foam_XXXXX.vts – the foam field (already produced by solar_foam_animation.py)  
craft_XXXXX.json – the interpolated state of every spacecraft for that frame

Load the pair in any VTK‑compatible 3‑D visualiser, scrub the timeline forward or backward, and watch your probes sail through a beautifully coloured, living spacetime‑foam landscape.
